Abstract: Fogacin and two novel fogacin derivatives, fogacins B  and  C,  were  isolated  from  the  rare  actinomycete  Actinoplanes  missouriensis.  Biosynthesis  of  fogacin  C  apparently  requires  b- alkylation of a polyketide chain. In fact, the fogacin biosynthetic  type  II  polyketide  synthase  (PKS)  gene  cluster  contains  a  hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA  synthase  (HCS)  cassette,  which  is  usually  responsible  for  b-alkylation  in  the  type  I  PKS  system.  Another characteristic of the fog cluster is that it encodes two sets  of ketosynthase (KS) and chain length factor (CLF). Inactivation  of  either  of  the  two  KS  genes  in  A.  missouriensis  and  heterologous  expression  of  the  HCS  cassette  with  either  of  the  two  KS–CLF  genes  in  Streptomyces  albus  indicated  that  each  KS–CLF has a different starter substrate specificity: one prefers  an unusual b-alkylated starter and the other prefers normal acetyl  starter.  This  study  expands  our  knowledge  on  HCS  cassette- dependent b-alkylation into the type II PKS system and provides  a  natural  example  of  combinatorial  biosynthesis  for  producing  diverse polyketides from different starter substrates.

Aromatic polyketides isolated from actinomycetes possess  diverse  structures,  and  many  of  them  exhibit  pharmaceutically  important  activities.[1]  Important  examples  are  the  antibiotic  tetracycline and the anticancer agent mithramycin. Most aromatic  polyketides  from  actinomycetes  are  synthesized  by  the  type  II  polyketide synthase (PKS) system.[1] In this system, ketosynthase  (KS),  chain  length  factor  (CLF),  and  acyl  carrier  protein  (ACP)  compose  a  minimal  PKS,  which  is  a  minimum  set  of  proteins  required for polyketide biosynthesis.[1] ACP binds covalently with  For internal use, please do not delete. KS and CLF form a heterodimer  and catalyze decarboxylative Claisen condensation for polyketide  elongation.[2]  First,  the  acyl  moiety  of  acyl-ACP,  which  is  called  the starter substrate, is transferred to the catalytic cysteine of KS.  Then  the  KS–CLF  heterodimer  catalyzes  decarboxylative  condensation  of  malonyl-ACP,  which  is  called  the  extender  substrate, with the starter acyl moiety to synthesize a b-ketoacyl- ACP. Iterative decarboxylative condensation of malonyl-ACP with  acyl-ACP  results  in  an  elongated  polyketide  intermediate.  The  synthesized polyketide intermediate is further modified by various  modification enzymes, such as ketoreductase (KR) and cyclase  (CYC).[1]  The  structural  diversity  of  aromatic  polyketides  is  established  by  the  diversity  of  starter  units,  the  condensation  number  catalyzed  by  KS–CLF,  and  the  diversity  of  modification  enzymes.

Alkylation of a polyketide chain is an important strategy to  generate polyketide diversity. Two systems are known for the a- alkylation of a polyketide chain: incorporation of alkylmalonyl-CoA  and  methylation  of  a-carbon  using  S-adenosylmethionine  (SAM).[3,4] The former is the most commonly observed strategy for  polyketide  alkylation,  and  various  alkyl  groups  such  as  methyl,  ethyl,  and  methoxy  can  be  introduced  into  a  polyketide  chain  using alkylmalonyl-CoA. In contrast to a-alkylation, b-alkylation of  a polyketide chain is rather unusual, but two systems have been  elucidated.[5–7]  In  2006,  Calderone  et  al.  reported  that  a  set  of  freestanding  enzymes,  which  are  encoded  by  a  genetic  locus  called  hydroxymethylglutaryl  (HCS)  cassette, act in trans for the b-alkylation of a growing polyketide  chain  in  the  type  I  PKS  system  (Figure  1A).[5,6]  This  system  consists  of  an  ACP,  an  acyltransferase  (AT),  a  KS  that  lacks  a  conserved Cys residue required for C-C bond formation, an HCS  homolog, and two enoyl-CoA hydratase (ECH) homologs, each of  which acts as a dehydratase or decarboxylase (Scheme 1A). First,  a malonyl moiety is loaded onto ACP by AT. Then KS catalyzes  the  decarboxylation  of  the  malonyl-ACP  to  yield  acetyl-ACP,  which serves as the acetyl nucleophile donor in the following b- alkylation step by the HCS homolog. The HCS homolog catalyzes  the  aldol  attack  of  the  acetyl  enolate  to  the  b-ketothioester  tethered on an ACP domain of type I PKS to generate an

- alkylation step by the HCS homolog. The HCS homolog catalyzes  the  aldol  attack  of  the  acetyl  enolate  to  the  b-ketothioester  tethered on an ACP domain of type I PKS to generate an HMG- ACP  thioester.  The  HMG-ACP  thioester  is  dehydrated  and  decarboxylated sequentially by the two ECH homologs to yield a  b-methylated intermediate. In 2013, as the second system for b- alkylation, Michael addition of an acetyl unit to an a,b-double bond  during  polyketide  extension  was  reported.[7]  This  reaction  is

catalyzed by a set of the KS domain and branching (B) domain.  These b-alkylation systems were reported only for the type I PKS  system; so far, no type II PKS has been reported to utilize these  b-alkylation systems. Here, we report a novel type II  PKS  system  that  utilizes  the  HCS  cassette-dependent b-alkylation  system.  First,  fogacin[15]  and  two  novel fogacin derivatives, including  a  b-alkylated  one,  were  isolated  by  A.  missouriensis  from  physicochemical  of  secondary  metabolites.  Fogacin  is  a  cyclic  octaketide  originally  isolated  from  Streptomyces  strain  Tü 6319.[15] Meanwhile, the fogacin  biosynthetic  gene  cluster  was  discovered  genome  sequence.  This  gene  cluster  contains an HCS cassette and two  sets  of  KS–CLF  genes.  This  HCS  cassette  was  to  synthesize  an  unusual  b-alkylated  starter  unit,  3-methyl-3-pentenoyl- Intriguingly,  one  KS–CLF  ACP.  heterodimer  was  indicated  to  prefer  this  unusual  starter  unit  for  the biosynthesis of a fogacin derivative, while the other KS–CLF  heterodimer  was  indicated  to  prefer  a  normal  acyl  unit  (acetyl- ACP) as a starter substrate. This is the first type II PKS system  reported  to  exploit  the  HCS  cassette-dependent  b-alkylation  system.  Isolation and characterization of fogacin derivatives from A.  missouriensis

By  physicochemical  screening  of  secondary  metabolites  produced  by  A.  missouriensis  in  six  different  media  (Q,  PYM,  Bennett Maltose, BE, mannitol soya flour, and YEME media; see  Supporting  Information  for  compositions),  we  discovered  three  putative  aromatic  polyketides  that  were  only  produced  in  Q  medium.  To  elucidate  the  structures  of  these  compounds,  we  isolated them and analyzed their molecular formulae using high- resolution  mass  spectroscopy  (HR-MS).  As  a  result,  the  molecular  formulae  of  these  compounds  were  revealed  to  be  C16H18O6  (m/z  329.1000  [M+Na]+;  calcd  for  329.0996,  1),  C22H28O10  (m/z  475.1575  [M+Na]+;  calcd  for  475.1575,  2),  and  C23H30O8 (m/z 435.2018 [M+H]+; calcd for 435.2013, 3). Compounds 1 and 2 were also analyzed by nuclear Overhauser  effect correlated spectroscopy (NOESY). The obtained NMR data  of  1  (Table  1)  suggest  that  this  compound  is  fogacin  (Figure  1A).[15]  By  comparing  the  1H  and  13C  NMR  data  of  1  with  those  previously reported,[15] compound 1 was unequivocally identified  as fogacin. Correlation between H-3 and H-13 was observed by  NOESY analysis, showing that C-13 and C-11 are located in trans  (Figure  1A).  This  relative  stereochemistry  is  identical  to  the  previously reported stereochemistry of fogacin (1).  In  comparing  the  NMR  data  between  fogacin  (1)  and  compound 2 (Table 1), 2 was revealed to be a fogacin glycoside.  HMBC  correlation  observed  from  H-1'  to  C-12  shows  that  the  sugar moiety binds to the carboxylic acid moiety of fogacin (Figure  1B).  The  relative  stereochemistry  of  the  sugar  was  further  analyzed  by  calculating  the  JH,H  coupling  constants  between  hydroxylmethine protons (Figure S1). As a result, this sugar was  revealed to be rhamnose. Because the JC,H coupling constant of  1'  was  177.4  Hz,  this  rhamnose  was  determined  to  be  a- rhamnose. [16,17] This novel fogacin derivative was named fogacin  B (2).

The NMR analysis of compound 3 (Table 1) suggests that it  has  a  similar  tricyclic  ring  system  as  fogacin  (1).  However,  this  compound showed additional signals from two sp2 carbons and  two methyl carbons, none of which were observed in fogacin (1)  (Table 1). HMBC analysis revealed that these signals are derived  from  a  trans-2-butenyl  moiety  attached  to  C-13  of  fogacin  (1)  (Figure 1C). In addition, compound 3 seems to possess a glycerol  moiety.  However,  HMBC  analysis  could  not  reveal  where  this  glycerol  moiety  is  attached. Genome scanning for the fogacin biosynthetic gene cluster  According  to  the  structural  similarity  between  fogacin  (1)  and  several  aromatic  polyketides  synthesized  by  type  II  PKSs,  such  as  actinorhodin,[18,19]  medermycin,[20]  and  granaticin,[21]  we  assumed that fogacin (1) is synthesized by a type II PKS system.  By  antiSMASH  analysis  of  the  genome  sequence  of  A.  missouriensis,[8,14] we discovered a gene cluster that encodes two  sets of KS (AMIS_50430 [FogA10] and AMIS_50640 [FogN]) and  CLF (AMIS_50440 [FogA9] and AMIS_50650 [FogO]) and post- PKS  modification  enzymes,  which  are  homologous  to  the  the  biosynthesis  of  actinorhodin,[18]  enzymes  medermycin,[20]  and  granaticin[21]  (Table  2  and  Figure  2).  We  predicted that this gene cluster is responsible for the biosynthesis  of  the  fogacin  derivatives,  and  we  named  it  the  fog  cluster.  As  described  below,  gene  disruption  analysis  confirmed  the  involvement of the fog cluster in fogacin derivative biosynthesis. The fog HCS cassette lacks AT and KS  genes required for acyl-ACP synthesis (Scheme 1A). Instead, an  LnmK  homolog  (45%  identity),  FogA7,  is  encoded.[25,26]  LnmK  catalyzes  the  acyltransfer  of  methylmalonyl-CoA  to  ACP  and  subsequent decarboxylation to provide propanoyl-ACP, which is  used  for  the  b-alkylation  of  polyketide  in  the  biosynthesis  of  leinamycin.  A  similar  enzyme  was  reported  in  lomaiviticin  biosynthesis;  it  also  provides  a  propanoyl  starter  unit  from  methylmalonyl-CoA.[27]  Therefore,  we  expected  that  FogA7  has  similar AT-decarboxylase (DC) activity to provide propanoyl-ACP  for b-alkylation.  (2) HCS cassette-related genes.  These five HCS cassette genes  (from  fogA7  to  fogA3  in  gene  organization)  seem  to  form  an  operon together with the genes involved in polyketide synthesis:  fogA12  (3-ketoacyl-ACP  synthase  [KAS]  III),  fogA11  (ACP),  fogA10  (KS),  fogA9  (CLF),  fogA8  (ACP),  and  fogA2  (KS).  We  speculate  that  FogA11  (ACP),  FogA10  (KS),  and  FogA9  (CLF)  compose a minimal PKS and that FogA12 (KAS III), FogA8 (ACP),  and  FogA2  (KS)  have  some  important  roles  in  HCS  cassette- dependent b-alkylated polyketide synthesis by the minimal type II  PKS. KAS III), FogA8 (ACP),  and  FogA2  (KS)  have  some  important  roles  in  HCS  cassette- dependent b-alkylated polyketide synthesis by the minimal type II  PKS.  FogA12  (KAS  III)  is  similar  to  AknE2  (47%)[28]  and  DpsC  (45%),[29,30] which are FabH-like enzymes encoded in type II PKS  gene  clusters.  These  FabH-like  enzymes  were  predicted  to  be  important  for  the  selection  of  the  specific  acyl  starter  substrate.  DpsC  was  reported  to  catalyze  either  the  first  condensation  between the starter and extender substrates or the transfer of a  specific starter acyl moiety to the ACP of a minimal PKS, or both,  but it still remains unclear whether DpsC catalyzes either or both  of  these  two  reactions  under  physiological  conditions.[29,30]  Anyway, we speculate that FogA12 has an important role in the  selection  of  the  specific  acyl  starter  substrate  by  minimal  PKS  FogA9–11. FogA2 (KS) shows homology to KSs of type I PKSs  such  as  KS3  of  ColI  (39%  identity)[23]  and  KS1  of  VirA  (43%  identity)[31].  Taking  into  consideration  the  chemical  structure  of  fogacin C (3), we speculate that FogA2 acts as a KS to produce  acetoacetyl-ACPFogA8  from  malonyl-ACPFogA8  (Scheme  1B,  see  below for ACPFogA8). In this paper, we report a novel type II PKS system that utilizes  enzymes  encoded  by  an  HCS  cassette  to  produce  b-alkylated  polyketides.  In  this  system,  the  HCS  cassette  enzymes  are  responsible for providing an unusual starter substrate produced  via  b-alkylation  of  a  polyketide  chain.  We  propose  that  this  unusual starter unit is synthesized as below (Scheme 1B). First,  FogA2  (KS)  catalyzes  the  condensation  of  two  molecules  of  malonyl-ACPFogA8 to synthesize acetoacetyl-ACPFogA8. Meanwhile,  FogA7  catalyzes  the  synthesis  of  propanoyl-ACPFogA6  from  methylmalonyl-CoA  and  ACPFogA6.  FogA5  catalyzes  aldol  condensation  between  propionyl-ACPFogA6  and  acetoacetyl- ACPFogA8  to  synthesize  2,3-dimethyl-2-hydroxyglutaryl-ACPFogA8.  Subsequent  dehydration  and  decarboxylation  catalyzed  by  the  ECH  homologs,  FogA4  and  FogA3,  produces  3-methyl-3- pentenoyl-ACPFogA8,  which  is  the  starter  substrate  utilized  by  (4  and  5)  produced  by

FogA10–FogA9  (KS–CLF).  FogA12  (KAS  is  probably  important  for  the  selection  of  the  starter  substrate  3-methyl-3- pentenoyl-ACPFogA8 and catalyzes the first condensation between  3-methyl-3-pentenoyl-ACPFogA8 and malonyl-ACPFogA11 and/or the  transfer  of  the  3-methyl-3-pentenoyl  moiety  from  ACPFogA8  to  ACPFogA11. The synthesized diketide intermediate or the 3-methyl- 3-pentenoyl  moiety  on  ACPFogA11  is  further  elongated  into  an  octaketide by FogA10–FogA9 (Schemes 1B and 2). Finally, the  synthesized  octaketide  intermediate  is  modified  by  several  modification enzymes to yield fogacin C (3) (Scheme 2). To  the  best  of  our  knowledge,  the  fog  cluster  is  the  first  characterized  type  II  PKS  gene  cluster  that  contains  an  HCS  cassette. Three putative biosynthetic gene clusters that possess  fogA1–A12 homologs were discovered in the genome database  (Figure  S5).  Saccharopolyspora  shandongensis  has  a  gene  cluster  that  is  considerably  homologous  to  the  fog  cluster.  This  gene cluster contains fogA2–A12 homologs as a putative operon,  just like the fog cluster. In addition, this cluster has an additional  copy  of  KS–CLF  genes  and  polyketide  modification  enzyme  genes that are homologous to fog genes. Therefore, this cluster  is likely to produce similar fogacin derivatives to those produced  by A. missouriensis. The other two gene clusters were discovered  from  two  different  strains  of  Streptomyces  pristinaespiralis  (strains HCCB 10218 and Pr11). These two gene clusters have  very similar gene organization and seem to evolve from the same  origin. In these gene clusters, the fogA2–A12 homolog operon is  divided  into  two  putative  operons,  fogA2–fogA8  and  fogA9– fogA12 homologs. Interestingly, these gene clusters also possess  an additional set of KS–CLF genes, although a transposase gene  is  inserted  between  the  KS  and  CLF  genes.  We  assume  that  these  HCS  cassette-harboring  type  II  PKS  gene  clusters  are  responsible for the biosynthesis of some b-alkylated polyketides.  The  fog  cluster  is  characteristic  as  a  type  II  PKS  gene  cluster in that it possesses an HCS cassette and two sets of KS– CLF genes. The HCS cassette enzymes and two sets of KS–CLF  with different starter substrate specificities are used to enhance  the structural diversity of fogacin derivatives. The  metabolites  were  extracted  twice  with  an  equal  volume  of  ethyl  acetate  under  acidic  conditions.  The  organic  layer  was  evaporated to dryness, and the residual materials were dissolved  in methanol (1 mL). Metabolites were analyzed by LC-MS using  an  HPLC  system  Agilent  1260  Infinity  (Agilent  Technologies)  equipped with a COSMOSIL 5C18-AR-II (2.0 × 150 mm, Nacalai  Tesque) column coupled with an amaZon SL (Bruker Daltonics,  Billerica,  Massachusetts).  The  compounds  were  eluted  with  a  linear gradient of water–acetonitrile containing 0.1% formic acid  (5%–50% acetonitrile) as a mobile phase at 0.3 ml/min.  Construction of plasmids for heterologous expression

A  DNA  fragment  containing  fogA9–A11  was  amplified  by  PCR (primers 19 and 20) using an appropriate plasmid of the A.  missouriensis  long  DNA  library  (for  genome  sequencing)  as  a  template  and  then  inserted  into  the  EcoRI  and  HindIII  sites  of  pUC19,  resulting  in  pUC19-fogA9–A11.  pUC19-fogA9–A11  was  digested with NdeI and HindIII, and the DNA fragment containing  fogA9–A11 was cloned into the NdeI and HindIII sites of pTONA5,  [40]  resulting  in  pTONA5-fogA9–A11.  The  tipA  promoter  was  amplified  by  PCR  (primers  21  and  22)  using  pIJ6021[41]  as  a  template. The obtained DNA fragment was inserted into the NdeI  site  of  pTONA5-fogA9–A11  to  construct  pTtipA-  fogA9–A11.  The  correct  direction  of  the  tipA  promoter  was  confirmed  by  DNA  sequencing.  For internal use, please do not delete. Submitted_Manuscript

fogA1–A12  possesses  unique EcoT22I (in fogA5) and SphI (in fogA9) sites. Therefore,  the region was divided into three fragments, fogA1-A5 (fragment  1), fogA5–A9 (fragment 2), and fogA9–A12 (fragment 3). These  three DNA fragments were amplified by PCR (primers 23 and 24  for  fragment  1,  25  and  26  for  fragment  2,  and  27  and  28  for  fragment  3)  using  the  A.  missouriensis  long  DNA  plasmid  as  a  template and then cloned into the HindIII-XbaI, HindIII-EcoRI, and  XbaI-EcoRI  sites  of  pUC19,  respectively,  resulting  in  pUC19- fragment_1, 2, and 3. pUC19-fragment_3 was digested with XbaI  and EcoRI, and the obtained fragment 3 was cloned into the XbaI  and  EcoRI  sites  of  pUC19-fragment_1,  resulting  in  pUC19- fragment_1-3.  pUC19-fragment_2  was  digested  with  EcoT22I  and  SphI,  and  the  obtained  fragment_2  was  cloned  into  the  corresponding sites of pUC19-fragment_1-3, resulting in pUC19- fogA1–A12.  pUC19-fogA1–A12  was  digested  with  HindIII  and  NdeI, and the DNA fragment containing fogA1–A12 was cloned  into the HindIII and NdeI sites of pTONA5, resulting in pTONA5- fogA1-A12. The tipA promoter amplified as described above was  cloned into the NdeI site of pTONA5-fogA1–A12 to obtain pTtipA- fogA1–A12.

The  chloramphenicol  resistance  gene  (Cm)  was  amplified  by PCR (primers 29 and 30) using pACYC as a template. The Cm  gene with homology arms and DraI sites was amplified by PCR  (primers 31 and 32) using the amplified Cm gene as a template.  The amplified fragment was introduced into E. coli strain GB05- dir[42]  carrying  pTtipA-fogA1–A12.  The  recombination  took  place  inside the cell to substitute fogA10–A9 with the Cm gene, which  is  bracketed  by  DraI  sites,  resulting  in  pTtipA-fogA1–A12DA10– A9::Cm. Next, the fogNO genes were amplified by PCR (primers  33  and  34).  The  amplified  fogNO  genes  and  pTtipA-fogA1– A12DA10–A9::Cm digested with DraI were assembled using the  Gibson Assembly system (New England Biolabs, Massachusetts,  USA), resulting in pTtipA-fogA1–A12[fogA9–A10::fogNO].  Heterologous expression of the fogA operon

Recombinant S. albus strains harboring pTONA5 (negative  control),  pTtipA-fogA9–A11,  pTtipA-fogA1–A12,  and  pTtipA-fogA1– A12[fogA10A9::fogNO]  were  pre-cultivated  in  R5MS  medium  (100  mL)  in  a  shaking  flask  at  30°C  for  2  days  on  a  reciprocal  shaker  at  120  rpm.  A  portion  (1  mL)  of  each  pre-culture  was  transferred  into  R5MS  medium  (50  mL)  in  a  shaking  flask  and  cultivated  at  the  same  condition  for  48  h.  To  induce  the  gene  expression, thiostrepton was added (final concentration; 5 µg/mL)  and cultivation was continued for additional 4 days. The cells were  removed  by  centrifugation  and  the  supernatant  was  extracted  three  times  with  an  equal  volume  of  ethyl  acetate  under  acidic  conditions.  After  evaporation  of  the  organic  phase,  residual  materials were dissolved in methanol (1 mL) for LC-MS analysis.  The sample was analyzed by LC-MS equipped with a COSMOSIL  5PYE packed column (2.0 × 150 mm, Nacalai tesque). A linear  gradient  of  water–acetonitrile  containing  0.1%  formic  acid  (5%– 100% acetonitrile) was used as a mobile phase at 0.3 ml/min.  Isolation and structural characterization of compounds 6 and  7

S.  albus  harboring  pTtipA-fogA1–A12  was  inoculated  into  R5MS medium (100 mL) in a shaking flask and pre-cultivated at  30°C for 2 days on a reciprocal shaker at 120 rpm. A portion (10  mL) of the pre-culture was transferred into R5MS medium (1 L) in  a 5-L culture flask and cultivated at 30°C on a rotary shaker. After  48  h,  expression  of  induced  by  adding  fogA1–A12  was  thiostrepton  (final  concentration;  5  µg/mL)  and  cultivation  was  continued for additional 2 days. Then Amberlite FPX66 resin (10  g)  was  added  to  the  culture  and  the  mycelia  and  resin  were  collected  by  centrifugation.  Metabolites  were  extracted  with  methanol  from  the  mycelia  and  resin.  b-Alkylated  SEK4  and  SEK4b were purified and characterized with the same method as  for compound 3. From a total of 4-L culture, pure compounds 6  (13.7 mg) and 7 (4.3 mg) were obtained. They were characterized  by  HR-MS  using  Agilent  6500  series  Accurate-Mass  Q-TOF  (Agilent Technologies), as well as NMR as described above.
